                <p><strong>Court Jurisdiction:</strong> 58th District Court - Holland Division, 12120 Fillmore Street, West Olive, MI 49460</p>

                <p>GRCC's Holland Lakeshore Campus has seen 14% enrollment growth and serves students throughout Ottawa County. If you're arrested in Holland or surrounding areas, your case goes to 58th District Court.</p>

                <p>The Holland area has different enforcement patterns than Grand Rapids. Ottawa County tends to be more conservative, and the court approaches may differ from the urban Grand Rapids court system.</p>

                <p><strong>Important: You need an attorney who practices in BOTH 61st District Court (Grand Rapids) AND 58th District Court (Holland).</strong> We do. We understand the different judges, prosecutors, and procedures in both jurisdictions.</p>

                <h2>Understanding Dual Proceedings: Criminal Court vs. GRCC Discipline</h2>
                <p>Most GRCC students don't realize they may face TWO separate proceedings after an arrest:</p>

                <h3>Criminal Court System</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Prosecuted by Kent County Prosecutor (Grand Rapids) or Ottawa County Prosecutor (Holland)</li>
                    <li>Constitutional rights protected (right to remain silent, right to attorney)</li>
                    <li>Burden of proof: "Beyond a reasonable doubt"</li>
                    <li>Potential outcomes: Conviction, plea deal, dismissal, diversion</li>
                    <li>Consequences: Jail time, fines, probation, criminal record</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>GRCC Student Code of Conduct</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Internal disciplinary process separate from criminal court</li>
                    <li>Lower standard of proof than criminal court</li>
                    <li>Can proceed even if criminal charges are dismissed</li>
                    <li>Potential outcomes: Warning, probation, suspension, expulsion</li>
                    <li>Consequences: Removal from programs, loss of enrollment</li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>Career programs have the strictest requirements:</strong> Nursing, dental hygiene, culinary, EMT, and other professional programs may dismiss students for criminal conduct even before a criminal conviction. These programs have accreditation requirements, clinical placement rules, and licensing board expectations that force them to act quickly.</p>

                <h2>Common Criminal Charges for GRCC Students</h2>

                <h3>Minor in Possession of Alcohol (MIP)</h3>
                <p>MIP is extremely common for traditional-age GRCC students (18-21). Michigan law prohibits anyone under 21 from consuming or possessing alcohol, with any blood alcohol content over 0.02%.</p>

                <p><strong>Current Michigan MIP Law (2018 reform):</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>First offense:</strong> Civil infraction (not criminal), fine up to $100</li>
                    <li><strong>Second offense:</strong> Misdemeanor, up to 30 days jail, doubled fines</li>
                    <li><strong>Third offense:</strong> Misdemeanor, up to 60 days jail, up to $500 fine</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Even though first MIP is now civil, it still shows up on background checks and can affect:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Transfer applications to 4-year universities</li>
                    <li>GRCC career program requirements</li>
                    <li>Scholarship eligibility</li>
                    <li>Employment in positions requiring background checks</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Fake ID Possession and Use</h3>
                <p>Using fake IDs to buy alcohol or get into bars is a misdemeanor with serious consequences. Downtown Grand Rapids bars have cracked down significantly - many now call police instead of just confiscating fake IDs.</p>

                <p><strong>Why this matters for GRCC students:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Nursing students:</strong> Crime of dishonesty can disqualify you from clinical placements</li>
                    <li><strong>Dental hygiene students:</strong> State licensing boards review criminal history including dishonesty offenses</li>
                    <li><strong>Business students:</strong> Accounting/finance positions often require clean records</li>
                    <li><strong>Transfer students:</strong> Universities view dishonesty convictions very seriously</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Drug Possession Charges</h3>
                <p><strong>This is the most serious charge for GRCC students because it affects federal financial aid.</strong></p>

                <p>Michigan legalized recreational marijuana, but it's still illegal for anyone under 21. GRCC students under 21 can be charged with:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>First offense: Civil infraction, $100 fine</li>
                    <li>Second offense: Civil infraction, $500 fine</li>
                </ul>

                <p>But here's what most students don't know: <strong>Drug convictions can result in immediate loss of federal financial aid eligibility.</strong></p>

                <p>The FAFSA asks about drug convictions that occurred while receiving federal student aid. If you answer "yes," your Pell Grant and federal loans can be suspended. For many GRCC students, this means you cannot afford to continue your education.</p>

                <p><strong>Other drug charges (prescription pills without prescription, cocaine, MDMA, etc.):</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Criminal charges (misdemeanor or felony depending on substance/amount)</li>
                    <li>Immediate federal aid suspension if convicted</li>
                    <li>Professional licensing denial (nursing, dental hygiene, etc.)</li>
                    <li>Inability to pass background checks for clinical placements</li>
                    <li>Transfer application rejections</li>
                </ul>

