                <h2>Protecting Your Financial Aid at GRCC</h2>

                <p>Financial aid is critical for community college students. Many GRCC students rely on federal aid to afford tuition. Understanding how criminal charges affect funding is essential:</p>

                <h3>Federal Financial Aid (Pell Grants, Federal Loans)</h3>
                <p>The FAFSA (Free Application for Federal Student Aid) includes a question about drug convictions:</p>

                <p><strong>Question 23:</strong> "Have you been convicted of possessing or selling illegal drugs for an offense that occurred while you were receiving federal student aid?"</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Alcohol offenses (MIP, fake ID, OWI) do NOT affect federal aid</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Drug convictions (marijuana, pills, cocaine, etc.) DO affect federal aid eligibility</strong></li>
                    <li>If convicted of drug possession while receiving aid, you lose eligibility for a period (1 year for first offense, 2 years for second offense)</li>
                    <li>If convicted of drug sale/distribution, longer ineligibility periods apply</li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>For many GRCC students, loss of federal aid means you cannot continue your education.</strong> Community college students often don't have family resources to pay out-of-pocket if aid is suspended.</p>

                <h3>Regaining Federal Aid Eligibility</h3>
                <p>After a drug conviction, you can regain eligibility by:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Completing an approved drug rehabilitation program</li>
                    <li>Passing two unannounced drug tests administered by an approved program</li>
                    <li>Or waiting until the ineligibility period ends</li>
                </ul>

                <p>However, drug rehabilitation programs cost money and take time - potentially derailing your education timeline.</p>

