                <h3>Will a criminal conviction affect my ability to transfer from GRCC to a 4-year university?</h3>
                <p>Yes, criminal convictions can significantly impact transfer applications. Many 4-year universities (including GVSU, WMU, Ferris State, etc.) require disclosure of criminal history on transfer applications. Universities may deny admission based on certain convictions, particularly those involving violence, drugs, or dishonesty. Even if admitted, criminal records can affect housing assignments, scholarship eligibility, and program admission (nursing, education, etc.).</p>

                <h3>Can I lose my federal financial aid because of a drug conviction?</h3>
                <p>Yes. Federal financial aid (Pell Grants, federal student loans) can be suspended for drug convictions. The FAFSA specifically asks about drug convictions that occurred while receiving federal aid. Alcohol offenses like MIP do NOT affect federal aid eligibility, but marijuana, cocaine, prescription drug, and other drug convictions DO. The suspension period depends on whether it's possession or sale/distribution and whether it's a first or repeat offense.</p>

